YELLOW FEVER, MONKEYS - VENEZUELA (MONAGAS, SUCRE)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Wed 9 Mar 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Epidemiological Bulletin, Ministry of Health, Venezuela,
Epidemiological Week No. 8, 20-26 Feb 2005 [translated from Spanish by
Mod.JGM, edited]
<http://www.msds.gov.ve/msds/modules.php?name=Downloads&d_op=getit&lid=67>

Environmental health zoonoses coordinator reports, 2 epizootics; 9th
epidemiological week
-----------------------------------------------
The 1st epizootic is reported in Monagas State, Aguasay community, Aguasay
parish, on the banks of the Oritupano river, Finca la Tribu. The epizootic
originated in the 2nd week of February 2005, and it has been confirmed by
bone findings and multiple testimonies. The Aguasay community has a 108
percent (?) yellow fever immunization coverage, and the surrounding
communities have the following coverage figures: Maturin, 63 percent; 100
percent in the neighboring parish, Rural del Sur; Ezequiel Zamora, 66
percent; Santa Barbara, 83 percent; and Cedeno, 83 percent. In the neighbor
state, Anzoategui, the yellow fever immunization coverage for the
surrounding community is: Freites, 86 percent.
The 2nd epizootic is reported in Sucre State (a state northwest of
Monagas), also in the oriental part of the country, in Valdez community,
Cristobal Rojas parish, Macuro-Los Chorros. This epizootic originated at
the end of February 2005, and it has been confirmed by the presence of
bone, monkey remains and multiple testimonies. The yellow fever
immunization coverage in Valdez community is 71 percent and for the
following communities is: Arismendi, 112 percent; and Marino, 85 percent.
Vaccination activities in the communities involved in the outbreak that had
not reached 100 percent coverage are being resumed. Also, rapid monitoring
in the communities with a higher than 100 percent coverage is being
performed, and an enhanced surveillance for jaundice and hemorrhagic
syndrome in the sentinel centers in the involved areas has also been
implemented.
